# Part I
# Foundation

# Chapter 1
# Goals

## 1.1 Purpose

The LinkLoader Specification defines the observable behavior of a
runtime service authority manager positioned between kernel
initialization and userspace execution.

LinkLoader is responsible for controlling service activation,
dependency management, authority delegation, and runtime startup
coordination.

This specification defines observable behavior only.

Internal implementation is unrestricted.

---

## 1.2 Objectives

A conforming implementation SHALL

• Register services.

• Validate manifests.

• Resolve dependencies.

• Grant runtime authority.

• Activate services.

• Track service state.

• Report diagnostics.

• Support deterministic startup.

---

## 1.3 Scope

This specification defines

• Runtime startup

• Service registration

• Authority management

• Dependency graphs

• Runtime activation

• Runtime shutdown

• Manifest format

• Service monitoring

This specification does NOT define

• CPU scheduling

• Memory allocation

• Filesystems

• Device drivers

• Interrupt handling

• Process scheduling

These remain responsibilities of the operating system.

---

## 1.4 Design Philosophy

LinkLoader follows six principles.

1.

Kernel remains minimal.

2.

Authority is centralized.

3.

Services start only when required.

4.

Dependencies are explicit.

5.

Startup is deterministic.

6.

Implementation remains unrestricted.

---

## 1.5 Terminology

Authority

Permission granted to execute.

Service

A managed userspace component.

Manifest

A service description file.

Dependency

Another service required before startup.

Activation

Granting execution authority.

Registry

The collection of known services.

---

## 1.6 Runtime Position

The conceptual startup model is

Firmware

↓

Bootloader

↓

Kernel

↓

LinkLoader

↓

Boot Services

↓

Runtime Services

↓

Shell / GUI

↓

Applications

---

# Chapter 2
# Architecture

## 2.1 General

LinkLoader SHALL execute immediately after kernel initialization.

The kernel SHALL transfer startup control to LinkLoader.

---

## 2.2 Responsibilities

LinkLoader SHALL

• Discover manifests

• Build dependency graphs

• Validate startup order

• Grant authority

• Start services

• Record service state

• Accept runtime activation requests

---

## 2.3 Authority Model

No managed service SHALL begin execution until authority has been
granted.

Authority SHALL be granted by LinkLoader.

Example

Application

↓

Activation Request

↓

LinkLoader

↓

Validation

↓

Authority Granted

↓

Service Starts

---

## 2.4 Runtime Lifetime

LinkLoader SHALL remain resident after boot.

It SHALL continue accepting activation requests until system shutdown.

---

## 2.5 Internal Design

Implementations MAY use

• Tables

• Graphs

• Trees

• Databases

• Hash Maps

Observable behavior SHALL remain equivalent.

---

## 2.6 Thread Safety

Concurrent activation requests SHOULD be handled safely.

Race conditions SHALL NOT produce duplicate service execution.

---

## 2.7 Startup Determinism

Given identical manifests,

startup ordering SHALL remain deterministic.

---

# Chapter 3
# Service Registry

## 3.1 General

Every managed service SHALL be registered.

Unregistered services SHALL NOT receive runtime authority.

---

## 3.2 Service Identifier

Every service SHALL contain

• Name

• Unique Identifier

• Executable

• Version

Identifiers SHALL be unique.

---

## 3.3 Manifest

Every service SHALL provide a manifest.

Required fields

Service Name

Identifier

Executable

Startup Mode

Permissions

Dependencies

Restart Policy

Version

Optional fields MAY be added.

---

## 3.4 Manifest Validation

Invalid manifests SHALL be rejected.

Examples include

Missing executable

Duplicate identifier

Circular dependency

Invalid startup mode

---

## 3.5 Registry Database

The registry SHALL contain

• Service Metadata

• Runtime State

• Dependencies

• Authority Status

• Failure Count

Implementations MAY store additional metadata.

---

## 3.6 Registry Updates

Registries MAY support

Dynamic registration

Dynamic removal

Version updates

Reloading

---

## 3.7 Compatibility

Unknown manifest fields SHOULD be ignored whenever practical.

Implementations SHALL preserve compatibility with previous manifest
versions whenever possible.

# Part II
# Runtime

# Chapter 4
# Dependency Resolution

## 4.1 General

LinkLoader SHALL resolve service dependencies before granting runtime
authority.

Services SHALL NOT execute until all mandatory dependencies have entered
the Running state.

---

## 4.2 Dependency Graph

The runtime SHALL internally construct a dependency graph.

Example

Filesystem

↓

Logger

↓

Network

↓

Desktop

↓

Deshell

The internal representation is implementation-defined.

---

## 4.3 Dependency Types

A dependency MAY be

• Required

• Optional

• Runtime

• Boot

Required dependencies SHALL be satisfied before startup.

Optional dependencies MAY be skipped.

---

## 4.4 Circular Dependencies

Circular dependency graphs SHALL be rejected.

Example

A → B

B → C

C → A

The runtime SHALL report a diagnostic.

---

## 4.5 Missing Dependencies

If a required dependency cannot be located,

the requesting service SHALL NOT receive authority.

---

## 4.6 Version Compatibility

Services MAY specify

Minimum Version

Maximum Version

Preferred Version

Implementations SHOULD validate compatibility.

---

## 4.7 Dependency Cache

Implementations MAY cache dependency graphs.

Cached graphs SHALL be invalidated whenever manifests change.

---

## 4.8 Dependency Diagnostics

Diagnostics SHOULD identify

• Missing dependency

• Circular dependency

• Version mismatch

• Invalid manifest

---

## 4.9 Summary

Dependency resolution SHALL complete before runtime authority is granted.

---

# Chapter 5
# Startup Pipeline

## 5.1 General

Startup SHALL occur in deterministic phases.

Each phase SHALL complete before the next begins.

---

## 5.2 Phase One

Registry Initialization

• Discover manifests

• Validate manifests

• Build registry

---

## 5.3 Phase Two

Dependency Resolution

• Build dependency graph

• Validate graph

• Reject invalid services

---

## 5.4 Phase Three

Authority Assignment

LinkLoader SHALL determine which services are eligible to execute.

---

## 5.5 Phase Four

Boot Services

Mandatory boot services SHALL start first.

Examples

Storage

Logging

Console

IPC

---

## 5.6 Phase Five

Runtime Services

Automatic runtime services SHALL start.

Manual services SHALL remain inactive.

---

## 5.7 Phase Six

User Environment

Shell

GUI

Desktop

Login Manager

Applications

MAY begin execution.

---

## 5.8 Startup Completion

Startup SHALL be considered complete when every required service reaches

Running

or

Failed.

---

## 5.9 Startup Logging

Implementations SHOULD record

Startup Time

Service Count

Failures

Warnings

---

## 5.10 Summary

The startup pipeline provides deterministic and repeatable system
initialization.

---

# Chapter 6
# Authority Management

## 6.1 General

Authority represents LinkLoader's permission for a managed service to
begin execution.

A managed service SHALL NOT execute without authority.

---

## 6.2 Authority Request

A request MAY originate from

• Boot

• Another Service

• User

• Application

• Administrator

---

## 6.3 Validation

Before authority is granted,

LinkLoader SHALL verify

• Service registration

• Manifest validity

• Dependency satisfaction

• Startup mode

• Runtime state

---

## 6.4 Grant

If validation succeeds,

LinkLoader SHALL grant execution authority.

The service MAY then start.

---

## 6.5 Denial

Authority SHALL be denied if

• Dependencies failed

• Service is disabled

• Manifest is invalid

• Duplicate execution is detected

---

## 6.6 Revocation

Implementations MAY revoke authority.

Revocation SHOULD stop future activations.

Running services MAY continue or terminate according to implementation
policy.

---

## 6.7 Duplicate Authority

A running service SHALL NOT receive duplicate authority.

Repeated activation requests SHOULD return the existing service state.

---

## 6.8 Authority Lifetime

Authority MAY remain valid

• Until shutdown

• Until service exit

• For a defined duration

Policy is implementation-defined.

---

## 6.9 Summary

Authority management forms the security boundary between startup requests
and service execution.

# Chapter 7
# Runtime Activation

## 7.1 General

After system startup, LinkLoader SHALL continue operating as the runtime
authority manager.

Services MAY be activated at any time.

---

## 7.2 Activation Sources

Runtime activation MAY originate from

• Applications

• Shell

• Desktop Environment

• User Request

• Another Service

• Administrator

---

## 7.3 Activation Pipeline

Every activation SHALL follow

Request

↓

Validation

↓

Registry Lookup

↓

Dependency Check

↓

Authority Decision

↓

Execution

↓

State Update

---

## 7.4 Service Launch

Upon successful validation,

LinkLoader SHALL launch the requested executable.

The executable path SHALL be obtained from the service manifest.

---

## 7.5 Duplicate Requests

If a service is already running,

LinkLoader SHALL NOT create another instance unless the manifest
explicitly permits multiple instances.

---

## 7.6 Runtime Dependencies

Services activated during runtime SHALL satisfy dependency
requirements before execution.

---

## 7.7 Activation Queue

Implementations MAY queue activation requests.

Queued requests SHOULD be processed in arrival order.

---

## 7.8 Runtime Failures

Activation failures SHALL generate diagnostics.

Failed activations SHALL NOT affect unrelated services.

---

## 7.9 Summary

Runtime activation extends LinkLoader functionality beyond system boot.

---

# Chapter 8
# Service Monitoring

## 8.1 General

LinkLoader SHALL maintain runtime information for every managed service.

---

## 8.2 Runtime States

Minimum states

Registered

Waiting

Starting

Running

Paused

Stopping

Stopped

Failed

---

## 8.3 State Changes

State transitions SHALL be recorded.

Implementations MAY expose runtime state through management APIs.

---

## 8.4 Health Monitoring

Implementations MAY periodically verify

• Process existence

• Heartbeat

• Response time

• Exit status

---

## 8.5 Unexpected Termination

Unexpected service termination SHALL update runtime state to

Failed

Restart behavior SHALL follow the configured restart policy.

---

## 8.6 Resource Information

Implementations MAY collect

CPU Usage

Memory Usage

Runtime Duration

Restart Count

Exit Code

---

## 8.7 Logging

Service events SHOULD be logged.

Examples

Started

Stopped

Restarted

Failed

Authority Granted

Authority Denied

---

## 8.8 Monitoring Interface

Implementations MAY expose runtime information through

• CLI

• API

• GUI

---

## 8.9 Summary

Monitoring provides runtime visibility into managed services.

---

# Chapter 9
# Runtime Messaging

## 9.1 General

LinkLoader MAY provide communication between managed services.

---

## 9.2 Message Types

Supported message categories MAY include

Activation

Shutdown

Reload

Status

Query

Notification

---

## 9.3 Service Requests

Managed services MAY request

Start Service

Stop Service

Restart Service

Query Status

Request Authority

---

## 9.4 Authority Requests

Authority requests SHALL be validated before execution.

Unauthorized requests SHALL be rejected.

---

## 9.5 Notifications

LinkLoader MAY notify dependent services when

• a service starts

• a service stops

• a service fails

• configuration changes

---

## 9.6 Reload

Configuration reloads MAY occur without restarting LinkLoader.

Services MAY receive reload notifications.

---

## 9.7 Shutdown Broadcast

During system shutdown,

LinkLoader SHOULD notify managed services before termination.

---

## 9.8 Message Reliability

Implementations SHOULD guarantee ordered delivery for messages between
LinkLoader and managed services whenever practical.

---

## 9.9 Summary

Runtime messaging allows LinkLoader to coordinate managed services after
system startup while remaining independent of kernel IPC mechanisms.

# Part III
# Configuration & Security

# Chapter 10
# Manifest Specification

## 10.1 General

Every managed service SHALL provide exactly one service manifest.

The manifest describes the service and provides the information required
by LinkLoader to determine startup behavior.

---

## 10.2 Required Fields

Every manifest SHALL contain

Service Name

Identifier

Version

Executable

Startup Mode

Dependencies

Authority Level

Restart Policy

---

## 10.3 Optional Fields

A manifest MAY additionally define

Description

Author

Working Directory

Arguments

Environment Variables

Timeout

Priority

Maximum Instances

Custom Metadata

---

## 10.4 Startup Modes

The following startup modes are standardized.

Automatic

Started during system startup.

Manual

Started only by explicit request.

On-Demand

Started when another service or application requests it.

Disabled

Never started.

---

## 10.5 Authority Level

Every service SHALL declare its required authority.

Examples include

Normal

System

Privileged

Kernel-Assisted

Implementations MAY define additional authority classes.

---

## 10.6 Dependency Declaration

Dependencies SHALL reference service identifiers.

Example

Filesystem

↓

Logger

↓

Network

↓

Desktop

The dependency graph SHALL remain acyclic.

---

## 10.7 Manifest Validation

LinkLoader SHALL reject manifests containing

Duplicate identifiers

Unknown startup modes

Invalid authority levels

Circular dependencies

Missing executables

---

## 10.8 Manifest Versioning

Every manifest SHALL contain a version.

LinkLoader SHOULD support backward-compatible manifest revisions.

---

## 10.9 Manifest Compatibility

Unknown optional fields SHOULD be ignored.

Mandatory fields SHALL always be validated.

---

## 10.10 Summary

The manifest is the canonical description of every managed service.

---

# Chapter 11
# Security & Authority Policy

## 11.1 General

LinkLoader is responsible for controlling execution authority for
managed services.

Execution SHALL NOT begin without authorization.

---

## 11.2 Trust Boundary

The trust boundary exists between

Request

↓

Validation

↓

Authority Decision

↓

Execution

Only validated services SHALL cross this boundary.

---

## 11.3 Authority Verification

Before granting authority,

LinkLoader SHALL verify

• Registration

• Manifest

• Dependencies

• Runtime State

• Startup Policy

---

## 11.4 Unauthorized Services

Unknown or unregistered services SHALL be denied authority.

Diagnostics SHALL be generated.

---

## 11.5 Authority Revocation

Authority MAY be revoked when

A service becomes invalid

A manifest changes

A dependency fails

Administrative action occurs

---

## 11.6 Privileged Services

Privileged services SHOULD be started only after successful authority
verification.

Implementations MAY require additional validation.

---

## 11.7 Service Isolation

Implementations SHOULD isolate managed services whenever practical.

Isolation mechanisms are implementation-defined.

---

## 11.8 Runtime Verification

Authority MAY be revalidated during runtime.

Revalidation SHOULD NOT interrupt healthy services.

---

## 11.9 Security Diagnostics

Typical diagnostics include

Unknown Service

Invalid Manifest

Authority Denied

Dependency Failure

Policy Violation

Duplicate Activation

---

## 11.10 Summary

Authority management forms the primary security mechanism defined by this
specification.

---

# Chapter 12
# Logging & Diagnostics

## 12.1 General

LinkLoader SHOULD record significant runtime events.

Logging assists debugging, monitoring, and compliance verification.

---

## 12.2 Logged Events

Recommended events include

System Startup

Registry Loaded

Service Started

Service Stopped

Service Failed

Authority Granted

Authority Denied

Manifest Loaded

Manifest Rejected

---

## 12.3 Log Levels

Standard log levels

Information

Warning

Error

Critical

Debug

---

## 12.4 Diagnostics

Diagnostics SHALL contain

Category

Identifier

Description

Timestamp

Service Identifier

Severity

---

## 12.5 Standard Diagnostic Codes

LL0001

Manifest Missing

LL0002

Invalid Manifest

LL0003

Duplicate Identifier

LL0004

Circular Dependency

LL0005

Dependency Missing

LL0006

Authority Denied

LL0007

Service Failed

LL0008

Executable Missing

LL0009

Registry Failure

LL0010

Internal Error

---

## 12.6 Persistent Logging

Implementations MAY retain logs across reboots.

Storage mechanisms are implementation-defined.

---

## 12.7 Log Rotation

Implementations SHOULD support log cleanup or rotation.

---

## 12.8 Compatibility

Diagnostic wording MAY differ.

Diagnostic meaning SHALL remain equivalent.

---

## 12.9 Summary

Logging provides standardized runtime reporting for LinkLoader
implementations.

# Part IV
# Conformance

# Chapter 13
# Conformance

## 13.1 General

An implementation SHALL satisfy every mandatory requirement defined by
this specification before claiming compatibility.

---

## 13.2 Mandatory Features

A conforming implementation SHALL implement

✓ Service Registry

✓ Manifest Validation

✓ Dependency Resolution

✓ Deterministic Startup

✓ Runtime Activation

✓ Authority Management

✓ Service State Tracking

✓ Diagnostics

✓ Startup Pipeline

---

## 13.3 Optional Features

Implementations MAY additionally support

• Service Priorities

• Plugins

• Live Manifest Reload

• Remote Management

• GUI Tools

• Monitoring APIs

• Performance Statistics

Optional functionality SHALL NOT modify mandatory behavior.

---

## 13.4 Compatibility Statement

An implementation MAY advertise

"LinkLoader Compatible"

only after implementing every mandatory requirement defined by this
specification.

---

## 13.5 Version Reporting

Implementations SHOULD report

Implementation Name

Implementation Version

Specification Version

Target Platform

Example

LinkLoader

Version 1.0

Specification 0.1

Target Doton-OS

---

## 13.6 Backwards Compatibility

Future specification revisions SHOULD preserve compatibility whenever
practical.

Breaking changes SHALL require a major specification revision.

---

## 13.7 Observable Behavior

Internal implementation MAY differ.

Observable runtime behavior SHALL remain equivalent.

---

## 13.8 Summary

Conformance ensures that independently developed implementations remain
compatible.

---

